{"parse":{"title":"Reliquary Shrine of Saint Eleutherius","pageid":19513081,"revid":536945155,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tournai_Kathedrale7.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Tournai_Kathedrale7.JPG/220px-Tournai_Kathedrale7.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"175\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Tournai_Kathedrale7.JPG/330px-Tournai_Kathedrale7.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Tournai_Kathedrale7.JPG/440px-Tournai_Kathedrale7.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"2731\" data-file-height=\"2171\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tournai_Kathedrale7.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The Reliquary Shrine of Saint Eleutherius, 1247, in the <a href=\"/wiki/Cathedral_of_Tournai\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cathedral of Tournai\">Cathedral of Tournai</a></div></div></div>\n<p>The great <a href=\"/wiki/Gilding\" title=\"Gilding\">gilt</a>-copper and <a href=\"/wiki/Vitreous_enamel\" title=\"Vitreous enamel\">enamel</a> <b>Reliquary Shrine of Saint Eleutherius</b> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Cathedral_of_Tournai\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cathedral of Tournai\">cathedral of Tournai</a> (<a href=\"/wiki/Belgium\" title=\"Belgium\">Belgium</a>), one of the masterpieces of <a href=\"/wiki/Gothic_art\" title=\"Gothic art\">Gothic metalwork</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> was commissioned by Bishop Walter de Marvis of <a href=\"/wiki/Tournai\" title=\"Tournai\">Tournai</a>, and completed in 1247,<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> on the occasion of the <a href=\"/wiki/Translation_(relics)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Translation (relics)\">retranslation of relics</a> of Saint <a href=\"/wiki/Eleutherius_of_Tournai\" title=\"Eleutherius of Tournai\">Eleutherius of Tournai</a>, traditionally the <a href=\"/wiki/Bishop_of_Tournai\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bishop of Tournai\">city's first bishop</a>. The shrine takes the architectural form of a <i><a href=\"/wiki/Chasse_(casket)\" title=\"Chasse (casket)\">chasse</a></i> or gabled <a href=\"/wiki/Casket\" title=\"Casket\">casket</a>; its more distant prototype is the gabled <a href=\"/wiki/Sarcophagus\" title=\"Sarcophagus\">sarcophagus</a> that was an established <a href=\"/wiki/Romanesque_art\" title=\"Romanesque art\">Romanesque</a> convention in Northern Europe, \"a form which was quite fitting,\" Marvin Ross observed in discussing the similarly shaped gilt-copper and enamel reliquary of <a href=\"/wiki/Saint_Amand\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Saint Amand\">Saint Amand</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Walters_Museum\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Walters Museum\">Walters Museum</a> \"since these ch\u00e2sses were in a sense also tombs\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> As with the prototypical tombs, a <a href=\"/wiki/Arcade_(architecture)\" title=\"Arcade (architecture)\">blind arcade</a> runs along the base, forming <a href=\"/wiki/Niche_(architecture)\" title=\"Niche (architecture)\">niches</a> with the protective seated figures of <a href=\"/wiki/Apostle_(Christian)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Apostle (Christian)\">Apostles</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Prophet\" title=\"Prophet\">Prophets</a>. In its gable end St Eleutherius appears, holding his <a href=\"/wiki/Crozier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Crozier\">crozier</a> in one hand and in the other a model of the cathedral with its five spires.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>The shrine was made in Tournai or its immediate vicinity, once part of a prolific production that is now all but lost; it has been attributed<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> to the workshop that was founded by <a href=\"/wiki/Nicholas_of_Verdun\" title=\"Nicholas of Verdun\">Nicholas of Verdun</a>, the leading goldsmith of <a href=\"/wiki/Mosan_art\" title=\"Mosan art\">Mosan art</a>, who completed the reliquary of Our Lady<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> in 1205. It is conserved in the Treasury of the <a href=\"/wiki/Cathedral_of_Tournai\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cathedral of Tournai\">cathedral of Tournai</a>, housed in the former <a href=\"/wiki/Chapter_house\" title=\"Chapter house\">chapterhouse</a>.\n</p><p>Two years following the completion of this reliquary, a separate one was made for the head of Saint Eleutherius, now lost with its contents.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Reliquary_Shrine_of_Saint_Eleutherius&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"Doubtless the most sumptuous of all midthirteenth century reliquaries now remaining to us\" was the opinion of Marvin Chauncey Ross (\"The Reliquary of Saint Amandus\", <i>The Art Bulletin</i> <b>18</b>.2 [June 1936: 187&#8211;197] p. 187).</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Otto von Falke and H. Frauberger, <i>Die Deutsche Schmeltzarbeiten des Mittlealters</i>, (Frankfort) 1904:105, gives the date of completion.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Ross 1936:187.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">The reliquary shrine was fully described and discussed by J. Warichez, <i>La cath\u00e9drale de Tournai et son chap\u00eetre</i> (Wettern) 1934, vol. I illus. pls. XVIII and XIX.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">By Max Creutz, in P. Clemen, ed. <i>Belgischer Kunstdenkm\u00e4ler</i> (Munich) 1923:147.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Also preserved at the cathedral of Tournai.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Ross 1936:192.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1262\nCached time: 20180901161531\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.052 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.066 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 177/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 817/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 118/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 2273/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.005/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 525 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   35.704      1 Template:Reflist\n10